<section xml:id="section-complex-fractions">

    <title>Complex Fractions</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>In this section, we will learn how to simplify complex fractions, which have fractions in the numerator and/or denominator of another fraction.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="aMswqN951OY" />
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Simplifying Complex Fractions</title>

        <p>Consider the rational expression 
            <me>\frac{\frac{6}{x-4}}{\frac{6}{x-4}+3}</me>
        It's difficult to quickly evaluate this expression, or determine the important information such as its domain. This type of rational expression, which contains a <q>fraction within another fraction,</q> is referred to as a <term>complex fraction.</term> Our goal is to simplify such a fraction so that it has a <em>single</em> numerator and a <em>single</em> denominator, neither of which contain any fractions themselves.</p>

        <p>A complex fraction has fractions in its numerator and/or denominator, like<me>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}</me>
        We need to simplify this so that the main numerator and denominator no longer contain fractions themselves. Here is the standard method to simplify this fraction:
        <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}\amp=\frac{1}{2}\div3</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{2}\div\frac{3}{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>What if the expression above was instead <m>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}}</m> though? We would no longer be able to simply multiply by the reciprocal, as we don't immediately know the reciprocal of that denominator <m>\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}</m>. Instead, we could multiply the external numerator and denominator by something that eliminates all of the internal denominators. (We'll use the LCD to determine this). For example, we will multiply <m>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}</m> by <m>\frac{2}{2}</m>:
        <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}\amp=\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}\multiplyright{\frac{2}{2}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <remark><p>In the last example, it's important to identify which fraction bar is the <q>main</q> fraction bar, and which fractions are <q>internal.</q> To see the role this plays, compare the two expressions below.
        <sidebyside widths="40% 14% 40%">
        <p><md>
            <mrow>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}\amp=\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}\multiplyright{\frac{2}{2}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
        </md></p>
        <p>vs.</p>
        <p><md>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{\frac{2}{3}}\amp=\frac{1}{\frac{2}{3}}\multiplyright{\frac{3}{3}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
        </md></p>
        </sidebyside>
        So <m>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{1}{\frac{2}{3}}</m> have different values, and simplifying each requires a slightly different approach.</p></remark>

        <p>To remove multiple fractions in a complex fraction, we need to multiply the numerator and denominator by those fractions' least common denominator, like in the next few examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the complex fraction <m>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The internal denominators are <m>2</m>, <m>3</m>, and <m>4</m>, so the LCD is <m>12</m>. We will thus multiply the main numerator and denominator by <m>12</m> and simplify the resutl:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}}\amp=\frac{\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}}\multiplyright{\frac{12}{12}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{1}{2}\multiplyright{12}}{\left(\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{4}\right)\multiplyright{12}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{4+3}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{7}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>The same concept can be applied to complex fractions with variables, like in the next few examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the complex fraction <m>\frac{\frac{6}{x-4}}{\frac{6}{x-4}+3}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To start, we will look at the internal denominators and identify the LCD of <m>x-4</m>. Our first step will then be to multiply the main numerator and denominator by this. Then we will simplify the resulting expression.
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\frac{6}{x-4}}{\frac{6}{x-4}+3}\amp=\frac{\frac{6}{x-4}}{\frac{6}{x-4}+3}\multiplyright{\frac{x-4}{x-4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{6}{x-4}\multiplyright{(x-4)}}{\left(\frac{6}{x-4}+3\right)\multiplyright{(x-4)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{6}{x-4}\multiplyright{(x-4)}}{\frac{6}{x-4}\multiplyright{(x-4)}+3\multiplyright{(x-4)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{6+3(x-4)}, \text{ for }x\neq 4</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{6+3x-12}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{3x-6}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{3(x-2)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2}{x-2}, \text{ for }x\neq 4</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-evaluate-complex-fraction-function-with-restrictions">
            <statement>
                <p>Calculate the following function values for <m>f(x)=\frac{\frac{x+2}{x+3}}{\frac{2}{x+3}-\frac{3}{x-1}}</m>.
                <ol label="a">
                    <li><p><m>f(4)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>f(0)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>f(-3)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>f(-11)</m></p></li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will determine each function value by replacing <m>x</m> with the specified number:
                <ol label="a">
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>f(\substitute{4})\amp=\frac{\frac{\substitute{4}+2}{\substitute{4}+3}}{\frac{2}{\substitute{4}+3}-\frac{3}{\substitute{4}-1}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{6}{7}}{\frac{2}{7}-\frac{3}{3}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{6}{7}}{\frac{2}{7}-1}\multiplyright{\frac{7}{7}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{2-7}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-\frac{6}{5}</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>f(\substitute{0})\amp=\frac{\frac{\substitute{0}+2}{\substitute{0}+3}}{\frac{2}{\substitute{0}+3}-\frac{3}{\substitute{0}-1}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{2}{3}}{\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{-1}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{2}{3}}{\frac{2}{3}+3}\multiplyright{\frac{3}{3}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{2}{2+9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-\frac{2}{11}</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p>When evaluating <m>f</m> at <m>-3</m>, we can quickly see that this results in division by zero:<md>
                        <mrow>f(\substitute{-3})\amp=\frac{\frac{\substitute{-3}+2}{\substitute{-3}+3}}{\frac{2}{\substitute{-3}+3}-\frac{3}{\substitute{-3}-1}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{2}{0}}{\frac{2}{0}-\frac{3}{-4}}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Thus <m>f(-3)</m> is undefined.</p></li>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>f(\substitute{-11})\amp=\frac{\frac{\substitute{-11}+2}{\substitute{-11}+3}}{\frac{2}{\substitute{-11}+3}-\frac{3}{\substitute{-11}-1}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{-8}{-9}}{\frac{2}{-8}-\frac{3}{-12}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{8}{9}}{-\frac{1}{4}+\frac{1}{4}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{8}{9}}{0}</mrow>
                    </md>Therefore <m>f(-11)</m> is undefined.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-simplify-complex-fraction-function-with-restrictions">
            <statement>
                <p>Completely simplify the function defined by <m>f(x)=\frac{\frac{x+2}{x+3}}{\frac{2}{x+3}-\frac{3}{x-1}}</m>. Then determine the domain of this function.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The internal denominators of this function are already factored, so we can immediately identify that the LCD of those is <m>(x+3)(x-1)</m>. We will thus multiply the main numerator and denominator by the expression <m>(x+3)(x-1)</m> and then simplify the resulting expression.
                <md>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{\frac{x+2}{x+3}}{\frac{2}{x+3}-\frac{3}{x-1}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{\frac{x+2}{x+3}}{\frac{2}{x+3}-\frac{3}{x-1}}\multiplyright{\frac{(x+3)(x-1)}{(x+3)(x-1)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{\frac{x+2}{x+3}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-1)}}{\left(\frac{2}{x+3}-\frac{3}{x-1}\right)\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-1)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{\frac{x+2}{x+3}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-1)}}{\frac{2}{x+3}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-1)}-\frac{3}{x-1}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-1)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{2(x-1)-3(x+3)}, \text{ for }x\neq -3, x\neq 1</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{2x-2-3x-9}, \text{ for }x\neq -3, x\neq 1</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{-x-11}, \text{ for }x\neq -3, x\neq 1</mrow>
                </md>
                In the original (unsimplified) funciton, we could see that <m>x\neq -3</m> and <m>x\neq 1</m>. In the simplified function, we need <m>-x-11\neq 0</m>, so we can also see that <m>x\neq -11</m>. Therefore the domain of the function <m>f</m> is <m>\{x\mid x\neq -11, -3, 1\}.</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark><p>
            Note that in <xref ref="example-simplify-complex-fraction-function-with-restrictions">Example</xref>, the denominator of <m>-x-11</m> could have the factor <m>-1</m> factored out. So an equivalent way to write this function would be:
            <md>
                <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{-x-11}, \text{ for }x\neq -3, x\neq 1</mrow>
                <mrow>f(x)\amp=\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{-(x+11)}, \text{ for }x\neq -3, x\neq 1</mrow>
                <mrow>f(x)\amp=-\frac{(x+2)(x-1)}{x+11}, \text{ for }x\neq -3, x\neq 1</mrow>
            </md>
        </p></remark>        


        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the complex fraction <m>\frac{2\left(\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}\right)+3}{\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}+4}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The only internal denominator is <m>x-2</m>, so we will begin by multiplying the main numerator and denoinator by this. Afterwards, we'll simplify the resulting expression.
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{2\left(\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}\right)+3}{\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}+4}\amp=\frac{2\left(\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}\right)+3}{\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}+4}\multiplyright{\frac{x-2}{x-2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\left(\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}\right)\multiplyright{(x-2)}+3\multiplyright{(x-2)}}{\left(\frac{-4x+3}{x-2}\right)\multiplyright{(x-2)}+4\multiplyright{(x-2)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2(-4x+3)+3(x-2)}{(-4x+3)+4(x-2)}, \text{ for }x\neq 2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-8x+6+3x-6}{-4x+3+4x-8}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-5x}{-5}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=x, \text{ for } x\neq 2</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>


        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the complex fraction <m>\frac{\frac{5}{x}+\frac{4}{y}}{\frac{3}{x}-\frac{2}{y}}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We multiply the numerator and denominator by the common denominator of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, which is <m>xy</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\frac{5}{x}+\frac{4}{y}}{\frac{3}{x}-\frac{2}{y}}\amp=\frac{\frac{5}{x}+\frac{4}{y}}{\frac{3}{x}-\frac{2}{y}}\multiplyright{\frac{xy}{xy}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\left(\frac{5}{x}+\frac{4}{y}\right)\multiplyright{xy}}{\left(\frac{3}{x}-\frac{2}{y}\right)\multiplyright{xy}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{5}{x}\multiplyright{\frac{xy}{xy}}+\frac{4}{y}\multiplyright{\frac{xy}{xy}}}{\frac{3}{x}\multiplyright{\frac{xy}{xy}}-\frac{2}{y}\multiplyright{\frac{xy}{xy}}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{5y+4x}{3y-2x}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the complex fraction <m>\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}}{1-\frac{x}{x^2-9}}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>First, we factor all denominators if possible:
                <me>\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}}{1-\frac{x}{x^2-9}}=\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}}{1-\frac{x}{(x-3)(x+3)}}</me>
                Next, we identify the common denominator of those three fractions, which is <m>(x+3)(x-3)</m>. We then multiply the main numerator and denominator by that expression:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}}{1-\frac{x}{x^2-9}}\amp=\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}}{1-\frac{x}{(x-3)(x+3)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}}{1-\frac{x}{(x-3)(x+3)}}\multiplyright{\frac{(x+3)(x-3)}{(x+3)(x-3)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\left(\frac{x}{x+3}+\frac{2}{x-3}\right)\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-3)}}{\left(1-\frac{x}{(x-3)(x+3)\right)\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-3)}}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\amp=\frac{\frac{x}{x+3}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-3)}+\frac{2}{x-3}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-3)}}{1\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-3)}-\frac{x}{(x-3)(x+3)}\multiplyright{(x+3)(x-3)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{x(x-3)+2(x+3)}{(x+3)(x-3)-x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{x^2-3x+2x+6}{x^2-9-x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{x^2-x+6}{x^2-x-9}</mrow>
                </md>
                Note that since both the numerator and denominator are prime trinomials, this expression can neither factor nor simplify any further.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

